PAPER

Effect of cosolvents on nano-conﬁned water: a molecular dynamics study†
Payel Das*
Received 9th January 2012, Accepted 21st February 2012 DOI: 10.1039/c2nr30070b

We present results from atomistic molecular dynamics simulations to characterize the effects of cosolvents, such as urea and guanidinium (Gdm) salts, on the water conﬁned in hydrophobic carbon nanotubes. We observed complete drying of the nanotube interiors of diameter ranging from 8 to 17 A  in urea. In contrast, the water population within nanotube cores smaller than 12 A  remains unaffected in GdmCl solution, whereas larger nanotube interiors become partially dehydrated with prevailing presence of stable Gdm+–Gdm+ dimers. The molecular arrangement and the lifetime inside the nanotube were found to be characteristics of a particular cosolvent. In both urea and GdmCl solutions, preferential cosolvent intrusion resulting in nanotube dehydration is driven by the stronger dispersion interaction of cosolvent than water with the nanotube. The partial drying of the hydrophobic core is attributed to guanidinium’s better hydration and weaker self-association propensity compared to urea, as well as to its moderate ion-pairing with strongly hydrated chloride ions. The Gdm+ induced dehydration varies with the charge density of counter-ions, as the presence of high charge-density sulfate ions impedes penetration of guanidinium, and consequent dehydration of the nanotube. These ﬁndings provide important insights into the effect of cosolvents on the nano-conﬁned water in a hydrophobic environment.

Introduction
The unique properties of nano-conﬁned water have been a subject of immense interest over the past few years,1–3 as such systems are ubiquitous in nature. Conﬁned water is relevant in many phenomena, ranging from protein folding4,5 and functions6 to clay swelling7 and frost heaving in soil.8 Studies of nanoconﬁned water can also aid the development of new nano-devices in aqueous environments.9 The highly unusual properties of conﬁned water originate from the weak interaction with the conﬁning wall combined with the local ordering of the hydrogenbonding network imposed by the conﬁnement.1 Conﬁned water can thus have different structure, dynamics, and phase diagram than bulk water.9–17
Investigation of conﬁned mixtures also reveals interesting modiﬁcations in the bulk-phase diagrams.18–22 Such knowledge is important, since many cosolvents naturally occur in cellular environments. At the same time, conﬁning effects on water can be critical for modulating the function of many biomolecules, such as proteins, DNA strands, and lipid bilayers. In fact, nanoconﬁned water is vital for functions of ion channel23 and chaperone6 proteins. Well deﬁned hydrogen-bonded solvent
IBM T.J. Watson Research Center, 1101 Kitchawan Road, Yorktown Heights, NY 10598, USA. E-mail: daspa@us.ibm.com; Tel: +01-914-945-2373 † Electronic supplementary information (ESI) available: Additional tables and ﬁgures on cosolvent-induced drying of nanotubes. See DOI: 10.1039/c2nr30070b
This journal is ª The Royal Society of Chemistry 2012

molecules buried inside the hydrophobic core are found in some proteins that are needed for their function.24,25 Thus, a detailed characterization of conﬁned binary mixtures can provide a better understanding of conﬁning effects in a cellular environment. In addition, such information is also relevant for practical applications, such as gas storage26 and selective drug delivery.27
Recently, we have studied the effect of urea on the water occupancy of carbon nanotube interiors.28,29 Carbon nanotubes serve as a model and easily controllable system for providing a clear quantitative picture of the nano-conﬁned solvent in a nonpolar medium.30 Our simulations revealed preferential occupation of urea molecules leading to dehydration of hydrophobic nanotube interiors in 8 M aqueous urea. In this study, we focus on understanding how the physicochemical nature of a particular cosolvent affects nano-conﬁned water. For this purpose, we have performed simulations of nanotubes immersed in aqueous urea and guanidinium (Gdm) salt solutions.
Gdm+ is a planar, bulky cation with low charge density. On the other hand, urea is less polar than Gdm+, has no net charge, and can form hydrogen bonds with each other. Both urea and guanidinium chloride (GdmCl) are widely used as protein denaturants, whereas guanidinium sulfate is a protein stabilizing agent. Given the distinct chemical nature of urea and Gdm+, we here characterize the differences in terms of their effects on the conﬁned water inside hydrophobic nanotubes. Preferential cosolvent intrusion resulting in dehydration of the nanotube core in both urea and GdmCl solution was observed; however, the extent of dehydration is notably different. A microscopic picture
