is provided that accounts for such differential effects of urea and GdmCl. The effect of counter-ions on nanotube–Gdm+ interaction is also explored. We hope that these results will provide a better understanding of cosolvent induced changes of the nanoconﬁned water in a non-polar cavity.

Simulation details
The initial coordinates of single-walled nanotubes (CNTs) were generated using the nanotube builder plugin of VMD software. We used (6, 6), (8, 5), (9, 6), (10, 8), and (17, 8) CNTs to study nanotubes with diameters ranging from 8.1 A  to 17.3 A  (Table S1†). The length of CNTs varies from 1.35 to 3.3 nm (see Table S1†).
Molecular dynamics (MD) simulations, 50–150 ns long, were run for an individual nanotube solvated in a cubic box of pure water, 8 M urea, 6 M aqueous GdmCl, and 6 M aqueous Gdm2SO4 solutions (see Fig. S1†). The CHARMM22 (ref. 31) (parameter set c32b1) force ﬁeld and TIP3P water model were used in this study. The parameters for guanidinium cation used here were taken from the standard CHARMM parameters for arginine (see Table S2†). We kept the position of the nanotube restrained by applying a harmonic constraint. The MD simulations were performed at 300 K in an NPT ensemble using the NAMD2 molecular modeling package32 with a 2 fs timestep. Periodic boundary conditions were applied in all directions. Full electrostatics was evaluated at every timestep. A cutoff distance of 12 A  was used to directly calculate the short-range electrostatic interactions. The particle-mesh Ewald (PME) method was used for the long-range electrostatic interactions. The van der Waals (vdW) interactions were treated with a cutoff distance of 12 A  and a switching function to smoothly truncate the vdW potential energy at the cutoff distance. All simulations were run using an IBM BlueGene/L supercomputer. The simulations of (6, 6), (8, 5), and (9, 6), solvated in 6 M GdmCl, were run for 50 ns. For the systems containing larger CNTs [(10, 8) and (17, 8)], the simulation length was equal to or longer than 100 ns. For comparison among results obtained for different CNTs, the number of solvent molecules was normalized with that for a 3.3 nm long CNT (Fig. 1).
Results and discussions
Comparison of urea- and GdmCl-induced changes of nanotube core hydration
Our simulations of the CNTs with diameter (d) smaller than 12 A  in 6 M GdmCl revealed no change in nanotube core hydration compared to that in pure water (Fig. S1†). This result is in contrast to the behavior of urea molecules, in which urea preferentially penetrates inside CNTs with d ranging from 8 to 17 A . The core of a larger (10, 8) CNT with d > 12 A  experiences remarkable increase in the Gdm+ population (Fig. 1, top). The interior of the (10, 8) CNT, the smallest one experiencing a locally enhanced population of Gdm+, is consistently ﬁlled with $7 Gdm+ molecules after 24 ns (at t ¼ 0 ns, the number of Gdm+ was 4). Thus, the local concentration of Gdm+ within the core becomes higher than 6 M: the water–Gdm+ ratio within the CNT averaged over all frames obtained during 100 ns MD is $3.8, which is signiﬁcantly lower than in bulk ($5.4). Similar behavior
