is observed for the (17, 8) CNT (Fig. 1, Bottom). This observation clearly demonstrates the preferential intrusion of Gdm+ into a purely hydrophobic interior.
Clearly, there are marked differences between urea and GdmCl in terms of cosolvent population and the resulting dehydration observed within a hydrophobic core. Urea completely dehydrates the nanotube interior with a diameter of 8–17 A , whereas in GdmCl solution partial drying was observed only for larger CNTs with d > 12 A . Fig. 2 shows the molecular arrangement of cosolvent molecules and their orientation with respect to the nanotube within a (10, 8) CNT. A prevailing existence of Gdm+–Gdm+ dimers is observed inside the
