nanotube. This observation is in agreement with previous simulations performed by Jungwirth and coworkers, which have shown pairing of guanidinium faces that are strongly waterdepleted.33 The presence of homo-ion dimers inside all nanotubes simulated in this study is evident also from the radial density proﬁles of cosolvents (Fig. S2†). The existence of homo-ion dimers presumably restricts intrusion of Gdm+ in smaller nanotubes. In addition, there is a clear preference in their orientation with respect to the nanotube axis, as indicated by the probability distribution of the angles formed between Gdm+ molecules and a (10, 8) nanotube. Two peaks are evident in the distribution, one around 20  and a second one around 160 , which implies that the planar faces of Gdm+ tend to orient either to the nanotube walls and/or to the ﬂat face of another Gdm+ ion. Each Gdm+ inside the nanotube is hydrated in its molecular plane and forms hydrogen bond(s) with 1–2 water molecules, in line with its very weak hydration property compared to other cations.34 On the other hand, urea molecules appear to self-aggregate inside the CNT by N–H/O hydrogen bonding with no preferential orientation with respect to the nanotube (Fig. 2). This feature allows them to form a single-ﬁle urea chain and dehydrate even smaller nanotubes.
Both Gdm+ and urea not only populate the interior of the CNT core, but also accumulate near the outer surface of all CNTs. Urea accumulation near the outer surface of the CNT is also much higher than that of Gdm+. As a result, the water– cosolvent ratio is $1.6 in urea solution near the outer surface, signiﬁcantly lower than what is found in aq. GdmCl ($3.2) for a (10, 8) CNT.
While single-ﬁle transport of water and small organic molecules has been extensively investigated through simulations,1,12,35,36 transport through larger CNTs largely remains unexplored. In this context, Goddard and coworkers have recently reported the thermodynamic picture of water conﬁned in nanotubes with diameters from 0.8 nm to 2.7 nm. Water within a 1.2 nm (10,8) CNT stays in an enthalpy-stabilized ice-like phase, whereas in larger CNTs (diameter larger than 1.4 nm) water remains bulk-like.14 We here characterize the kinetics of water as well as of both cosolvents inside nanotubes by
Fig. 3 Cumulative distributions of the residence times, Presidence, of H2O (pure water), Gdm+ (6 M GdmCl) and urea (8 M urea) inside a (10, 8) CNT. Inset: crossover of residence times of urea and Gdm+ at $65 ns.
This journal is ª The Royal Society of Chemistry 2012

computing their residence times (lifetimes). Fig. 3 shows the cumulative distributions Presidence (t < s) of the lifetime s of urea, guanidinium, and water molecules inside the nanotube. Clearly, both cosolvents stay much longer than water inside the nanotube, with maximal lifetimes of urea, guanidinium and water being 92 ns, 100 ns and 13 ns, respectively. In general, urea molecules have long lifetimes inside a nanotube due to their high aggregation propensity. However, there is a clear crossover at a higher residence time of $65 ns due to stable Gdm+–Gdm+ dimers that stay notably longer than the single guanidinium molecules inside the nanotube. Similar results were found for a (17, 8) nanotube (Fig. S3†).
A common dispersion interaction driven mechanism for cosolvent-induced drying of nanotubes
The primary driving force of the observed phenomenon can be evaluated by calculating the loss/gain of energy (both electrostatic and dispersion) for each guanidinium and water molecule in the ﬁrst solvation shell (<5 A ) of CNT while moving to the nanotube core. For this purpose, the interaction energy of each water–guanidinium molecule with the environment was estimated during the ﬁrst 2 ns of the MD, long before water and the Gdm+ population inside a (10, 8) nanotube reaches equilibrium (see Fig. S4†). We found that the loss in electrostatic interaction energy with the rest of the system for each Gdm+ is $2.8 kcal molÀ1 as the ion moves toward the CNT. At the same time, each water molecule loses $3.0 kcal molÀ1 in electrostatic interaction energy while approaching CNT. Thus, clearly the electrostatic interaction cannot be the driving force for the preferential occupancy of Gdm+ within the nanotube. On the other hand, there is a signiﬁcant stabilization in the vdW interaction energy for Gdm+ ($5.9 kcal molÀ1) compared to water ($1.8 kcal molÀ1) as it moves near the CNT (Fig. S4†). Thus, each Gdm+ gains about 3.1 kcal molÀ1 (À5.9 + 2.8 kcal molÀ1) on average as it penetrates the CNT, while each water loses about 1.2 kcal molÀ1 (À1.8 + 3.0 kcal molÀ1) for the same process. This result clearly demonstrates that both Gdm+ and urea penetration into the nanotube core are primarily driven by vdW interaction energy, consistent with previous ﬁndings revealing attractive dispersion interactions of urea37 and Gdm+ 38 with hydrophobic polymers/ plates.
This driving force with stronger vdW interactions can also be seen from the interaction energy of each water–Gdm+ molecule with a (10, 8) nanotube (CNT only in this case; there is only vdW interaction energy present between the neutrally charged CNT and cosolvent–water) (Fig. 4). The interaction energy of a urea molecule with the (10, 8) CNT immersed is also shown for comparison. Both guanidinium and urea form stronger dispersion interaction with the nanotube than water ($À2.5 kcal molÀ1). The average CNT–Gdm+ vdW interaction energy ($À11.7 kcal molÀ1) within the core is slightly higher than the CNT–urea vdW interaction energy ($À10.6 kcal molÀ1). The average CNT–chloride dispersion interaction energy is $À3.5 kcal molÀ1. In the current study, the carbon atoms of the nanotubes were modeled using the CHARMM parameters for the aromatic carbon. The strong dispersion interaction of guanidinium with aromatic carbon atoms found here is consistent with the recent report by Mason et al., which has shown
