preferential interaction of Gdm+ with aromatic cosolutes over aliphatic cosolutes.39 The stronger interaction with nanotube, along with the presence of stable homo-ion dimers, allows guanidinium to stay longer than urea inside nanotube cores.

Chemical nature of the cosolvent determines the hydration of nanotubes
From the Ow–Ow and Ow–Hw radial distribution functions (RDFs) and Hw–Ow hydrogen bond distance distributions (Fig. S5†), it appears that both urea and guanidinium have little effect on the structure and hydrogen bonding of water, consistent with previous simulation data.40,41 A noticeable change in the Ow–Ow RDF is observed in the region 3 A  < r < 7 A  in GdmCl solution, while the ﬁrst coordination shell and the hydrogen bonding of water remain unperturbed. This change is similar to the pressure induced perturbation of the tetrahedral water structure reported in the literature.45 Nevertheless, the distinct dehydration of nanotubes in urea and GdmCl solutions can be explained in terms of their inherent chemical nature, as discussed below.
There are clear differences between two cosolvents in terms of hydration and self-association propensity, as evident from the cosolvent–cosolvent and cosolvent–water pair RDFs (Fig. 5). Urea has much higher propensity to self-associate than Gdm+, whereas Gdm+ is better hydrated than urea in bulk water, due to its ionic character and H-bonding interactions with water. Fig. 5 further shows that urea hydrogens make weaker hydrogen bonds than Gdm+ with water, which is evident from a reduced peak height and the peak shifting to larger distance. A similar conclusion can be obtained also from the probability distributions of hydrogen bond distances between Gdm+–water and urea–water (Fig. S5†). Gdm+ hydrogens form strong hydrogen bonds with water oxygens closely mimicking water–water hydrogen bonds, as manifested by the position agreement of the ﬁrst peak in the O–H RDF (Fig. 4) as well as in the hydrogen bond distance distributions (Fig. S5†). This stronger hydrogen bonding with water could be attributed to the higher negative
2934 | Nanoscale, 2012, 4, 2931–2936

Fig. 5 Pair radial distribution functions showing (top) cosolvent– cosolvent and cosolvent–water interactions and (bottom) hydrogen bonding interactions between water and cosolvent.
charge on nitrogens of Gdm+ (À0.8) than those of urea (À0.62). The better hydration of Gdm+ compared to urea elucidates the incomplete drying of the nanotube core in the aqueous GdmCl solution, which is augmented by the presence of strongly hydrated ClÀ ions (see below).
Effect of counter-ions on Gdm+ accumulation inside nanotubes: ClÀ vs. SO42À
The (10, 8) nanotube core was found to be ﬁlled with 5–7 ClÀ ions (Fig. 1); however ClÀ ions enter the core following Gdm+ due to their moderately attractive (ionic and hydrogen bonding) interactions with guanidinium cations.42 To evaluate the inﬂuence of anions on modulating the interaction of guanidinium with the nanotube, we have also simulated nanotubes in aqueous Gdm2SO4 solution that is known as a protein stabilizing agent. Sulfate is positioned further left of the Hofmeister series and has higher charge density than chloride. Sulfate stabilizes proteins, whereas chloride is essentially neutral. Our simulations show that the presence of sulfate ions completely impedes penetration of guanidinium ions, and consequent dehydration, within the (10, 8) nanotube (Fig. 6). Interestingly, in this case Gdm+ leaves the nanotube following sulfate. The preferential exclusion of sulfate from the hydrophobic nanotubes is due to its higher tendency to form hydration complexes that reside away from hydrophobic surfaces. Such a tendency of sulfate ions can lead to
This journal is ª The Royal Society of Chemistry 2012

View Article Online

Published on 01 March 2012. Downloaded by University of Massachusetts - Amherst on 6/6/2020 11:46:36 PM.

Furthermore, the Gdm+-induced dehydration varies with the charge density of counter-ions, as the presence of high chargedensity sulfate ions impedes guanidinium-induced dehydration. These results suggest that the water population in a non-polar nano-conﬁnement can be modulated by addition of cosolvents. Since many cosolvents naturally occur in cellular environments, our results might aid toward a better understanding of nanoconﬁned water in biological systems including proteins in vivo.

Acknowledgements
We thank Ruhong Zhou, Zhen Xia, and Bruce Berne for useful discussions. We also thank Rahul K. Das and Silvina Matysiak for comments on this manuscript. This work is supported by the IBM Blue Gene Science program.

Fig. 6 (a) Ion penetration and (b) hydration within a (10, 8) CNT core in 6 M Gdm2SO4 and in 6 M GdmCl solutions.
increased hydrophobic interaction compared to pure water, which is purely an entropic effect.43 In addition, stronger pairing of Gdm+ with sulfate,44 compared to that with chloride, leads to preferential exclusion of Gdm molecules from hydrophobic nanotubes. This observation that hydration of a hydrophobic core remains unaffected in Gdm2SO4 solution is likely associated with its protein stabilizing ability.
Conclusions
This study provides a quantitative comparison of urea and GdmCl induced changes on the hydration of a hydrophobic nanotube core, which is primarily driven by the stronger dispersion interaction of the cosolvent than water with the hydrophobe. As revealed in our study, the water population of nanotube cores with diameters smaller than 12 A  in GdmCl remains unaffected, as the core cannot accommodate Gdm+ homo-ion dimers. In contrast, nanotube cores with diameters ranging from 8 to 17 A  are exclusively dehydrated in urea. A purely hydrophobic nanotube core with a diameter larger than 12 A  is primarily populated by fully dehydrated nano-size urea aggregates. The same nanotube core also experiences higher local concentration of GdmCl within; however, it is only partially dehydrated due to better hydration and lower self-association tendency of Gdm+ than urea. Stable Gdm+–Gdm+ dimers are found inside all nanotubes with diameters larger than 12 A . The molecular arrangement and the lifetime inside the nanotube were also found to be characteristics of a particular cosolvent.
